column168: The driver noticed while waiting for a tire repair a small slow dip leak in the valve assembly. He then contacted his dispatcher after placing a spill bucket below the leak. Superior then called ERTS who in turned dispatched US Environmental to investigate and secure the release. It was determined that apparently the bolts on the valve assembly had become loose. The contractor tightened up the bolts and the leaked stopped. The three absorbent pads were then disposed of and the tanker was sent on it's way to the terminal for further inspection and delivery.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Misaligned Material, Component, or Device
column168: A BNSF train crew reported GATX 7566 (DOT 111A100W2 tank car) with product emanating from its fill hole closure. GATX 7566 was cordoned off in the siding track. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 7566. Intact shipper seal DUP 106915 was removed from fill hole closure. The responder reported that the fill hole cover was not completely closed against the fill hole nozzle. The cover was ajar as it rested atop the shoulder of the pressure relief securement bolt. The remaining three fill hole securement swing bolts were secure. The responder loosen the securement bolts to check the fill hole gasket which was found misaligned. Product outage was deemed appropriate. The responder cleaned and properly positioned the fill hole gasket. The fill hole cover was closed and all fill hole securement bolts were properly positioned and tool tightened. BNSF seal 002470 applied to fill hole closure. Dried product spillage on GATX 7566 and on the ground was neutralized with baking soda. Securement was completed by 1320 hrs. CDT, 11/02/2010.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

Trailer was floored out with plenty of dunnage.  Shipment was secure.  1 5 gallon metal pail was found leaking on the bottom of the skid.  Pail had buckled.  No evidence of forklift puncture.  No evidence of a puncture from a nail on the skid etc..  Pail was not in direct contact with anything other than the other pails on the skid and none of them contributed to the damage of the pail. column168: NATX 303984 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard was reported with fresh product stains on its side shell. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected NATX 303984. The responder reported intact seal NDPS 011002 removed from valve housing cover to inspect valves and fittings. The sample port valve appeared to be the source of the product release. A severe thunderstorm in the area caused the responder to dismount the tank car, postponing final securement activities. NATX 303984 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard. On 11/02/2010, contract responders completed securement by closing the sample port valve 2 1/2 turns. The sample valve's closure plug was only hand tight. The plug was removed, cleaned, plug threads Teflon taped and reapplied securely. The contractors cleaned the spillage inside the valve housing area and the sides of NATX 303984 with a soap solution and a pressurized water rinse. Rinsing liquids were captured by plastic tarping that was placed under NATX 303984. Afterwards, BNSF seal 1299 was applied onto the valve housing cover. The responders reported no observed ground impact from spillage and cleaning activities.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: On 11/1/2010 at 02:30 hrs. at Stanley yard in Walbridge, OH, CSXT personnel reported UTLX 202676, a loaded tank car of Xylenes, leaking liquid from its top area. CSXT  dispatched an emergency response contractor, Eagle/SWS. Eagle/SWS personnel advised product was noted on both sides of the manway nozzle/cover but was rapidly evaporating. They reported two of eight manway cover bolts were less than tool tight and tightened these bolts. CSXT moved UTLX 202676 to and from and liquid leak was noted at the interface of the manway cover and manway nozzle near the manway cover safety bolts. At 08:33 T. J. Mannas, Mgr.-HazMat, CSXT inspected UTLX 202676 with Eagle/SWS personnel. Seal "SUNCOR028404" was intact on the manway cover. The manway cover gasket was inspected. At 09:10 T. J. Mannas contacted Mr. E. Patterson (610-246-0843), Sunoco R+M, Philadelphia, PA. Mr. Patterson advised he would dispatch personnel from Union Tank Car Company, Oregon, OH to replace manway cover gakset with Durlon 9000 (present gasket same material). At 11:25 Mr. Ray Spencer, Supervisor-Field Operations, Union Tank Car Company, Oregon, OH (419-698-3820) and his personnel replaced the manway cover gasket. CSXT moved the tank car to and from and a liquid leak was noted at the interface of the manway cover and manway nozzle near the manway cover safety bolts. Union Tank Car Company personnel further tighened the manway cover bolts and repositioned the manway cover on its nozzle but to no avail. Mr. Spencer advised the leak was due to a "warped manway cover." Mr. Patterson was advised of this. Mr. Patterson advised he would furnish a tank car to accomplish transfer of UTLX 202676. UTLX 202676 was switched to an isolated track pending transfer.    A special switching move was required for this incident.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause code: 200  NARRI code: 5 (5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60
column169: Incident was discussed with Mr. E. Patterson, Sunoco Incorporated R+M for corrective actions.

column168: A rolloff container loaded with hazardous waste sludge was parked in the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility.  A driver picked up the box to deliver it to the disposal site.  When the box was being raised up in the air to be loaded onto the truck, approximately 20 gallons of liquid spilled out of the rear portion of the cover onto the ground.  A response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the material, placing it back into it's original container, along with some contaminated gravel and dirt.  The load then continued to the intended disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The waste was to be a solid, but the liquid content was too high and caused the liquid to separate and spill from the load.  The shipper was immediately notified and advised that we cannot accept this material until the liquid content is reduced.  The shipper agreed to modify their process to remove more liquid.

column168: During a routine yard check at the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility, a van trailer containing hazardous waste was found to be leaking.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, and entered the trailer.  The spill was contained and the trailer taken to the receiving area of the intended waste disposal facility where it was unloaded.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage container along with all clean up debris associated with the spill.  The trailer was cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound and placed back into service.
column169: The drum was leaking from the bottom seam.  There was no evidence of leaking when picked up, nor were there any causes for the drum to leak involving the load--no sharp objects or load shifting.  The drum appeared to be defective.  The shipper was notified of the incident.

On November 5, 2010 at approximately 0945 hours an IMTT Operations employee was attempting to load a ALL Chem Trans Corp. tanker truck with Methyl Ethyl Ketone (MEK)when the tanker compartment overflowed.  The tanker had two compartments, one with an available capacity of 2500 gallons and one with an available capacity of 1500 gallons.  The IMTT Operator mistakenly positioned the tanker truck to load 2,020 gallons of MEK into the trailer compartment with the smaller capacity.  When the truck rack meter read 1560 gallons, MEK began overflowing out of the trailer and onto the containment pad.  The operation was immediately shut down and excess product was pumped out of the loading hatch.  The area was wiped down and the loading of the trailer resumed without further incident.
column169: The incident was reviewed by IMTT Management and the employee.  Appropriate action was taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: The Shreveport yard reported an odor from UTLX 900552, residue: Last Contained Methyl Mercaptan//2.3//UN1064.  Yard crew detected and reported odor to tower. Carl Unddenberg investigated and found no odor adjacent to the car, on the ground by the ladder, but reports later came in from another yard crew reporting odor again.  KCS hazmat notified mobilized Specialized Response Solutions for safety qualified response. The Louisiana State Police was notified per state requirement. Also, notification to shipper has been completed through Chemtrec. The hazmat response team arrived at 7:30 a.m 11/14/10. The packing gland nut on the B-End liquid line of the tank car was tighten about  turn to stop the small leak. No other leaks was found of the tank car.    Note to report, item 27, amount in package, was estimated by preparer. This action was required to facilitate data acceptance by defective DOT IT system edits. Specifically, this estimated quantity was required: (1)because the shippers only provided bulk quantities on shipping paper, as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements; and (2)because the DOT e-system requires data in this field to facilitate report acceptance.     KCS emergency mitigation services were activated to provide for special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, dedicated internal management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory reporting as appropriate.  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 may apply as services require.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.

column168: The Horizon Trader was in route from San Juan Puerto Rico to Elizabeth, New Jersey. One was a non hazardous reefer container KLIU920015 that perhaps has some diesel fuel in the fuel tank of the refrigeration unit's power plant and the other was a loaded IMO portable tank of hazardous flammable waste UN1993 in tank FIBU125189-7.  The loss of the cargo occurred between 11/11 and the morning of 11/12/2010.  The tank cargo was moving on waste manifest #000351391VES.  A NRC report was immediately filed upon discovery of the loss.  The US Coast Guard was notified immediately as well.  The captain has filed a 2692 report.

Driver failed to check the clean out cap on the trailer to insure it was tight before presenting the trailer to the shipper for loading.  After loading shipper also failed to secure the cap.  As the driver was exiting the facility the cap came off and approximately 2 gallons of product was spilled onto the trailer and ran onto the tractor.  A very small amount, less than one gallon, dripped to the ground.  The cap was replaced and tightened at that point. Since the it was immediately outside the shipper facility, LA hazmat allowed the shipper to clean the spilled product from the roadway and dispose of the waste through their normal disposal process.  An outside contractor OilMop was contracted to clean the tractor and trailer and also handled the proper disposal of the waste which resulted from cleaning.  After cleaning the unit was released to proceed to destination without further incident.

column168: While performing normal switching duties within the Oak Island Classification Yard facility, Newark, NJ, local CR yard crew noted product residue on top of tank car GATX 29646, load, Tripropylene.  When car was moved out of the class yard onto track #64 for isolation and ease of access for repair, crew and CR Trainmaster T. Pilger noted product release from manway cover area while car was under movment.    Further inspection by CR Risk Manager A. Richter, and REACT Environmental Services R. Gould, noted the manway cover bolts to be adequately tool tight, but when bolts were released and cover opened, found the manway cover gasket grooved/compressed, whereby not permitting a tight seal.  Gasket that was applied and inspected as offered by shipper, Sunoco, Oregon, OH, was noted to be adhered to the manway cover gasket surface by an adhesive.  The gasket had to be scraped off.  A Viton manway nozzle gasket was used for replacement and manway cover closed.  All other fittings and valves inspected with no exceptions.  Car was moved back and forth by CR crew, and no further product release was noted.      Also noted the DOT specification stenciling of the car (111A100W1) was missing from both sides of the car.  Tank Car qualification stenciling noted car was last qualified "2008" by "GAGA".  Car was held on track #64, and a Mobile Repair Unit contracted by the shipper, reapplied the missing stenciling on Monday, November 8, 2010.  Car was okayed for movement to original destination.

column168: A shipment of hazardous waste in plastic supersacks was on the dock at the intermediate truck transfer facility.  When being loaded on a trailer for the intended waste disposal facility, approximately 1 pint of liquid material was found on the dock beneath the sacks.  The material had seeped out the bottom of one sack.  A response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and cleaned up the spilled material with absorbent materials.  The entire shipment was repacked into suitable salvage drums for further transportation.  The Tennessee Emrgency Management Agency was called and issued case number 2066 to the incident.  The shipment was then loaded into a trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility.
column169: The liquid content of the material was too high.  The material was described as a solid.  The shipper was notified of the incident and will insure a proper liquid content is shipped in the future.

column168: The tractor trailer was involved in a head on collision with a pick up truck apparently going the wrong way on the freeway. The result was the tractor trailer over turning and leaving the roadway. The rear man way cover was buried into the ground. A transfer of material was performed in which 1000 gallons was not accounted for. When the truck was up righted, the rear man way cover wing nuts were sheared off. The material had entered the soil turning it into a sludge like material. The material was excavated and staged on site until approval could be obtained for disposal. The site was back filled with soil and lime per the request of TN DEC. It was then graded, seeded and straw was placed down to return it to its original state.

During a routine yard check at the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility, a vacuum box was noticed to be leaking a small amount of material from the top flange.  The box was parked in containment.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, and cleaned up the spill immediately with an absorbent material.  A trough was placed underneath the leak until the sample could be analyzed and the shipment accepted for disposal.  The shipment was then disposed of along with all clean up materials at the intended waste disposal facility.  The vacuum box was placed out of service until the leaking flange could be replaced.
column169: The bin showed no signs of leaking when received from a third party hauler at the ten day storage yard.  The movement during transportation forced some liquid content of the solid material through the defective flange.  The third party hauler was advised of the leak and took the vacuum box out of service until maintenance could replace the flange.

column168: Kansas City yard reported odor being detected from GATX 200053 while being switched in zone 5, track 6. Safety qualified responders found the pipe connection from the pressure plate to the sample valve slightly loose causing a small release.  The pipe connection was thighted 1/4 turn correcting the release.     Note to report, item 27, amount in package, was estimated by preparer. This action was to facilitate data acceptance by defective DOT IT system edits. Specifically, this estimated quantity was required: (1)because the shippers only provided bulk quantities on shipping paper, as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements; and (2)because the DOT e-system requires data in this field, using same units of measure as found in the capacity field, to facilitate report acceptance. KCS will continue to report in this fashion unit instructed differently by DOT or PHMSA.    KCS emergency mitigation services were activated to provide for special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, dedicated internal management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory reporting as appropriate.  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 may apply as services require.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  Also, please reference http://nar.aar.com/ for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: On 11/10/2010 approx. 4:30 pm a Stericycle vehicle was parked in our yard. It was noticed when the vehicle was moved to our loading dock and the back door was open, blood was leaking out. Approx. 500 mL of blood was spilled in the back of the truck and on the ground near our loading dock. The damaged containers were repackaged. Blood on the ground and in the back of the vehicle was clean-up and the area was disinfected by Stericycle employees. CT DEP was notified case # 2010-6756.

A van trailer containing 4 flex bins of hazardous waste arrived at Clean Harbors Bristol CT facility  The Flex bins were transferred to another Clean Harbors van enroute to its intended waste disposal facility. Two Clean Harbors employees during their daily inspection noticed that there were 4 leaking flex bins; the van was put in a containment area at the plant. A response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer and unloaded the leaking flex bins. The flex bins were repacked into 16 metal drums. The trailer floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service for continued transport to intended disposal facility.

United States Environmental Services (USES), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the B-end liquid line valve 1 and  turns open and the plug was less than tool tight allowing vapor to release from the car. On November 05, 2010, upon receipt, review and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and subsequently released for transportation

A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day in-transit facility pending final delivery to the destination facility.  While at this location, it was discovered that a small amount of material had escaped from the package onto the floor of the van trailer.  Facility personnel assembled a response team to enter the trailer and address the source of the leak.  Upon inspection, it was discovered that a waste stream containing lab trash inadvertently contained a small amount of residual liquids that escaped through the side wall of the fiberboard IBC.  The crew proceeded to re containerize the contents of the leaking container along with all debris and clean-up supplies used to contain the release and decontaminate the trailer floor.  At the conclusion of the response activities, the material was placed back on the trailer and was sent to the intended waste management facility where it was accepted and processed without incident.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or staining was observed that would have indicated that a small amount of liquid was included in the package.  The shipper has been advised that any lab trash containing residual liquids must be segregated out and shipped in a container suitable for liquids

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation.  During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 2 gallons of material had escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the container.  Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised container into a suitable salvage drum.  In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum.  Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed.  Drivers will continue to inspect each container before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity.   IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all container used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

column168: On 11/12/2010 at 00:05 hrs. personnel at the CSXT Avon Yard in Avon, IN, discovered GLNX 34593, a residue tank car of Ammonia Anhydrous, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, CHS Inc., was contacted via Chemtrec #2010-11-12-00009. IDEM (Mark 317-694-3965) was also notified. Summit Environmental, RJ McFatridge, 812-459-9564, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the PRD O-ring leaking. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mary  Blel, 651-355-6941. Summit Environmental personnel replaced the O-ring and stopped the leak. The car was then released for transport to destination.    This incident did require a special switching move.  A 7.1 QA Non conformance report is required for this incident.    Cause code: 414  NARRI: 5 (4+9+2) x (2+0) = 150

column168: A BNSF train yarding in the railyard facility derailed entrained SHPX 208283 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) on its side. SHPX 208283 sustained rail burn damage on its side shell with subsequent shell compromise during movement after derailing. The rail burn compromise was located at mid-tank level on the right side near the A-end of SHPX 208283. Commodity spillage from SHPX 208283 was channeled and contained in a fabricated pit with lining applied. The remaining commodity inside SHPX 208283 was transferred into tanker trucks. The product loaded in these tank trucks was transferred into another suitable tank car on 11/18/2010 without further incident. Captured product in the lined pit was vacuumed up for future filtering and recycling. Impacted soil was excavated for appropriate future disposal.

column169: • It has been determined that the cause of the damage was one nail coming out from a wooden skid that punctured the bottom of the plastic jerrican. All relevant staff has been notified of the discrepancy and made aware that a such build up condition developed this situation. Standard Operating Procedures for handling staff have been reviewed. There has been some additional recommendations, included but not limited to:  Use only wood (skids or boards) that have been carefully inspected for nails or damaging objects.  Avoid the use of "inverted" skids unless other forms of build up are inappropriate.  The findings of this event should be disseminated through build up/loading staff worldwide. The training department should make reference to this event into the training program.  The auditing and DG team should check for build up process involving this practice and discuss accordingly.

column168: The waste shipment was loaded onto the truck at the facility by facility's personnel. The drums are typically placed directly on the floor of the truck. During the loading process and unbeknownst to the forklift operator at the time, one drum was set on top of a loose bolt inside the truck. The affected drum received a small puncture (1/8 inch) to the bottom edge of the drum.It is unclear as to the exact time the leak started, but shortly after the driver left the facility, he stopped on thes outhbound shoulder of US highway 61 approximately 7 miles south of Winona, MN. During this stop, the driver performed a vehicle check and noticed that there was a small amount of material leaking out of the side of his trailer.The driver estimated that approximately 1 quart or 3 Ibs of material had dripped onto the shoulder of the highway.The material is thick and viscous and did not run off of the asphalt roadway.The driver waited until the leak appeared to stop and attempted to cover the material with "oil-dry" and then proceeded to return to the facility where he picked the load up from. The driver contacted the facility to describe the incident. It was at this point the Safety, Health,& Environmental manager was notified and he proceeded to make the regulatory notifications of the hazardous waste release to the Minnesota Duty Officer. After returning to the facility the truck was unloaded to determine which drum or package had leaked. When the leaking drum was identified, it was apparent that only a small amount of waste material had escaped from the drum.The damaged drum was removed from the manifest and was later repackaged at the facility for shipment to an appropriate TSDF at a later date.
column169: On the facility end, we will be developing a pre-shipment checklist for our folks to go through each time they make a hazardous waste shipment. Part of that checklist will be to perform an inspection of the truck/trailer to ensure that it is in good condition and that the truck/trailer itself does not pose any hazards while loading the waste materials.

column169: Material being transfered will be done so using a pump instead of nitrogen pressure if at all possible. Nitrogen pressure will be minimized if and when used.

column168: While loading liquid ethylene portable tank, a leak was observed on the body of the fire block valve to the pressure building coil.  The pressure building coil is a heat exchanger on the container that is used to off load product, and the fire block valve is a spring loaded valve that can be "tripped" in the event of a leak to isolate the liquid side of the exchanger.  The container was unloaded back to the storage tank once the leak was found, and the in-house emergency response team stood by until the portable tank was empty of liquid ethylene.  After purging portable tank of ethylene/vapors, tank was sent to repair shop for further evaluation and repair.
column169: A formal root cause of the failure will be conducted by tank owner/lessee.  Tank Owner/lessee was notified of leak and tank lessee has informed Eastman that their maintenance facility pre-inspection process will include an additional leak check to ensure that leaks due to valve and piping failures can be identified and repaired prior to tanks being sent in for filling.

column168: On 11/18/10 at 14:44 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Southover yard in Savannah, GA, discovered DOWX 72248, a residue tank car of Methyl Acrylate, Stabilized, emitting an odor from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Flocryl, was contacted via CHEMTREC 2010-11-18-00204.  Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line closure plug less than tool tight with residual product about the ball valve. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to Flocryls representative, John Sullivan at 912-884-8717. Eagle/SWS personnel opened the liquid line ball valve to allow the residual product to return to the container. Eagle/SWS applied Teflon tape to the closure plug threads and then tightened the plug tool tight. The rail car was released for transportation.    This incident did not require a special switching move.    A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 120  NARRI: 5 (4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70
column169: This is the second non accidental release from Flocryl in less than ten (10) days.  All operators should be made aware of the recent incidents and emphasis should be placed on "spot checking" tank cars prior to being released for transportation.

column168: On 11/19/10 at 17:07 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Florence Yard in Florence, SC, discovered DNAX 321002, a loaded tank car of Acetonitrile, Crude, leaking from the bottom outlet valve.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Dana Transport Systems, was notified via Chemtrec report number 2010-11-19-00164. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet valve operating handle in the open position and the secondary securement cap less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's / EMES representative, Kellie Ziegler at 843-225-8318. HEPACO personnel closed and pinned the operating valve handle, then secured the closure cap tool tight. The leak was secured and the shipper was contacted to correct the original waybill documentation. On 11/23/10, CSX received the modified shipping documentation and the rail car was released to destination.    This incident did require a special switching move.   A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required.    Cause Code: 148  NARRI: 5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80
column169: Review proper securement procedures with operators to ensure compliance with the regulations.  Staff submitting waybills need to be completely familar with process.  The original waybill (802-052632-130398 dated 10/13/10) submitted to the Union Pacific classified the tank car as non hazardous using STCC 2818163.

column168: A citizen reported to BNSF that a passing train had an entrained tank car that was leaking contents from the top of this tank car. The identified BNSF train was stopped on main track after the BNSF train crew was alerted of a possible leaking tank car in their train. After train inspection, the train crew reported entrained CGTX 30444 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with product wetness on its side shell. CGTX 30444 was carefully set out of the train at a nearby transfer track. A BNSF responder assisted by the local F.D. reported that inspection of CGTX 30444 revealed that the liquid valve was in the full open position and this valve's closure plug was not applied. This condition allowed product to escape from the open orifice at the liquid valve during rail movement. The valve was closed and its closure plug was applied and tool tightened. Securement was completed by 1510 hrs. CDT, 11/02/2010. The F.D. responders applied oil absorbent on all observed impacted ground areas. An environmental contractor captured product dripping off the side shell of CGTX 30444 and cleaned spillage from its side shell and side ladders. Additional remediation of ground impact areas was accomplished. Captured spillage and spent cleaning supplies were earmarked for appropriate disposal.     On 11/11/2010 inspection of CGTX 30444 at the BNSF railyard in Temple, TX revealed that the liquid valve may be leaking again. A BNSF responder aided by contract responders inspected CGTX 30444. Inspection revealed that the liquid valve's flange bolts were loose and a small leak was detected at the ball valve/flange threaded connection. The responders removed the valve, cleaned and applied sealant to the threaded areas. Gasket material was applied to the flange plate and the flange bolts were tool tightened.  The valve was reinserted and properly tool tightened. Afterwards, no further evidence of product leakage was detectable.  FRA Movement Approval FRA-10110785 was granted to continue transport of CGTX 30444 to its destination for unloading and then leak proof pressure testing of CGTX 30444.  CGTX 30444 arrived at its destination for unloading on 11/23/2010 without further incident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While making a delivery, a leak occurred from the valve during sample test.  Approximately 0.5 cup of free product released to the containment bucket beneath the valve, and was contained immediately.  The free product did not affect ground surface or release to any surface soils or waters of the state.  Customer assisted in absorbing free product within bucket, the Slay Transportation Co., Inc. driver changed the valve connection, and proceeded with offload without further incident. No further action was required.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a faulty valve connection, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column169: BE AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.  WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, WHEN USING BLADES, ESPECIALLY THE LONG BLADS, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT.  DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING, ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICAL, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY  PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column168: SHIPPER: KODAK c/o RYDER RENO AWB RNO 8572590434 YUL                       On 11/12/2010 the DHL Dangerous Goods Hotline received a call in regard to a shipment that had leaked in the warehouse at the DHL Service Center at 1395 Air Cargo Way, Suite 129, Reno, NV 89502 on 11/11/2010.  The shipment was bagged and moved to the secured DG Area.  The MSDS that accompanied the shipment indicated the contents as PR 600 Alkaline Plate Cleaner, classified as Caustic Alkali Liquid, NOS (disodium metasilicate).  The shipment was not tendered to DHL Express as a dangerous goods shipment.  This shipment had not yet entered DHL's transit system and did not move via air.  A second piece from this shipment did move via air to the SFO Service Center in San Francisco, CA, where it was stopped.  This second piece did not leak.  Additionally, it was not tendered to DHL Express as a dangerous goods shipment.  A separate 5800.1 report will be generated for it.    MULTIPLE REPORT:  SHIPPER: Kodak do Ryder Reno AWB# RNO 8572590434 YUL  On 11/12/2010 the DHL Dangerous Goods Hotline received a call in regard to an undeclared dangerous goods shipment that moved via air transport from RNO to SF0 and was held at the DHL Service Center located at 682 McDonnell Road, San Francisco CA 94128. The MSDS that accompanied the shipment indicated thecontents as PR600 Alkaline Plate Cleaner, classified as Caustic Alkali Liquid NOS (disodium metasilicate). The shipment was not tendered to DHL Express as a dangerous goods shipment. It did not have any DC marking, labeling or a Shipper’s Declaration for Dangerous Goods. This shipment did not leak. It will be held at the SF0 Service Center for FAA investigation.

column168: AT COMPLETION OF OFF-LOADING 5,000 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE SUNNY SOL 100 PLUS JCI DRIVER OBSERVED THE USUAL RUSH OF AIR THROUGH THE 2' PVC DISCHARGE HOSE AT COMPLETION OF UNLOADING. AT THAT MOMENT THE 2" CAM-LOCK CONNECTION OF HOSE DISENGAGED FROM CUSTOMER TANK AND BEGIN TO SHIP, BLOWING A MIST OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE RESIDUE STILL WITHIN HOSE. JCI DRIVER WAS IN PROPER RELATION TO THE CONTROLS OF 5,000 GALLON FRP BULK TANK TRAILER AND QUICKLY SHUT OFF 2" VALVE ON 5,000 GALLON FRP TANK TRAILER WHICH CONTROLS 2" PVC HOSE. TWO OF THE CUSTOMER'S EMPLOYEES WERE IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA' MIST DID CONTACT ONE OF THESE TWO EMPLOYEES, BUT ONLY REQUIRED A RINSING AT AN EMERGENCY SHOWER. NO ONE REQUIRED ANY TYPE OF FIRST AID OR HOSPITALIZATION, BOTH RETURNED TO WORK.
column169: WAS FOUND THAT THE 2" CAM LOCK FITTING ON CUSTOMER TANK DID NOT HAVE THE 2-12" X 18" POLYETHYLENE VELCRO BANK SECURED UPON THIS CAM LOCK FITTING. THE JCI DRIVER WAS USING A (DOUBLE FEMALE 2" CAM LOCK) FITTING ON OUTLET OF THE 5,000 GALLON FRP BULK TANK TRAILER. THIS 2" DOUBLE CAM LOCK FITTING REQURED THE TWO (2) 2-1/2" X 18" VELCRO BANDS JCI DRIVER HAD IN THIS POSSESSION. JCI DRIVER DID NOT HAVE A THIRD VELCRO FITTING FOR THE CUSTOMER'S SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TANK 2" CAM LOCK FITTING. JCI-TORRANCE SINCE THIS INCIDENT NOW SUPPLIES ALL DRIVERS WITH THREE (3) 2-1/2" X 18" POLYETHYLENE SECURING BANDS FOR THE 2' CAM LOCK FITTINGS.

column168: The shipment from Virginia transported by SJ Transportation Company arrived at the Veolia ES Technical Solutions, L.L.C.  (Veolia) facility located in West Carrollton, OH for final disposal on November 10, 2010. Upon arrival, a Veolia employee noticed that one of the drums had leaked while in transit.  The drums were offloaded to gain access to the drum that had leaked and it was determined the leak occurred because the 3” bung on the top of the drum was not secured properly.      To correct the situation, the bung was replaced and tightened to prevent any future leaking.  The drum was then placed into an 85-gallon salvage drum and placed into storage until processed on-site for disposal.
column169: Veolia has informed the shipper of the incident so that they can take the appropriate steps to prevent a reoccurrence.

column168: BNSF was notified by Woodward, OK authorities that a passing BNSF train with entrained tank cars was leaking. The identified BNSF train was stopped on main track at station Tangier for crew inspection. The train crew reported entrained TILX 193983 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was leaking product from its bottom outlet valve (BOV). BNSF and response contractors inspected TILX 193983 and reported that the bottom operated BOV operating handle was not pinned in the closed position and the bottom outlet cap (BOC) was not applied and was hanging from its securement chain. The responders closed the BOV operating handle and wedged a wooden shim to secure it in the closed position which ended any further product release. The BOC was applied and tool tightened. The unpinned BOV operating handle allowed it to vibrate to an open position and with no BOC in place to contain product resulted in this product release from the BOV. Two other entrained tank cars were also noted with their BOC's not applied and hanging from their securement chains with no product leaks detected; responders applied these BOC's and tool tightened them. This BNSF train was reinspected by BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders upon its arrival at Amarillo, TX. Responders resecured the BOV bottom operating handle on TILX 193983 by pinning it with a bolt/nut application in its closed position. Remediation of spillage at the main track train stop location was initiated after the rain events in that area ceased. Responders remediated spillage by soil aeration with applications of Micro-Blaze. Also, previous sites were entrained TILX 193983 may have leaked product on the ground were inspected and no evidence of product spillage was noted.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder's inspection of an inbound unit train in the railyard (inspection triggered by a previous securement issue of these entrained rail cars) revealed GATX 200271 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with product drips from the bottom operated bottom outlet valve's (BOV) bottom outlet cap (BOC). The responder reported the BOV operating handle in an open position, the BOV valve handle was not pinned and no shipper seal was present. The BOC was found tool tight and the condition of the BOC gasket was not inspected on this loaded tank car. The BOC gasket was suspected of not sealing properly, allowing product to escape via the tight BOC. The responder closed the BOV and properly pinned the BOV operating handle in the closed position. Afterwards, no further product drips were observed.  BNSF seal numbered 06157272 was applied to the BOV. Product spillage evaporated.

column168: A BNSF mechanical car inspector in the railyard reported an inbound shipment in GATX 37081 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was emanating a strong rotten-egg type odor. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected GATX 37081. The responder reported 1 of 8 manway securement bolts not tool tight; and the manway gasket was dirty, deteriorated and pinched. No liquid release was noted only commodity vapor/odor. A new manway gasket was applied to the manway closure and all manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened. Securement was completed by 1202 hrs. PST, 11/19/2010. Afterwards, no further commodity odor was prevalent. Intact shipper seals numbered 05532 and 05534 were replaced by BNSF seals numbered 06157101 and 06157286 respectively.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Star Transport, LLC made a delivery of gasoline to the Shop N Mart at 5008 Aldine Bender in Houston, Texas.  Immediately following the delivery, a gasoline leak was discovered from the port hole on the UST at the fueling station.  An unknown third party utilized water to wash the affected surface, which resulted in the impact to a nearby storm drain.  The Harris County Public Health Department and Houston City Fire Department were contacted to respond.  Upon arrival on site, the Houston FD applied foam to the affected surface.  It was reported that approximately 50-100 gallons of gasoline had been released.  However, later determined that approximately 5% gasoline, 95% water were observed.  Garner Environmental Services, Inc. of Deer Park, Texas was dispatched by Star Transport, LLC. to perform the cleanup.  Upon inspection of the site, it was confirmed to be 95% water solution, which had impacted the storm drain. Absorbent material was applied to the asphalt surface and Garner Environmental Services, Inc. proceeded to flush the storm sewer system to remove residual product from the storm drain, while collecting wash water at the outfall.  Two (2), 55-gallon drums of spent absorbents and approximately 300 gallons of wash water, were generated during the cleanup.  Garner Environmental Services, Inc. will coordinate disposal in accordance with local, state and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be the result of an overflow while offloading, due to a gauge miscalculation, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Star Transport LLC will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: At approximately 0950, CDT, 11-11-2010, I was advised by Terminal Manager, J. Godney of a report of an ammonia smell in the vicinity of car #PLMX 135275 in track# BC38. I subsequently proceeded to track #38 and checked car with Ammonia test paper via inspection ports confirming the presence of ammonia. Upon opening the protective housing cover which was not sealed, I determined the source of leak was emanating from the Pressure Relief Device (PRD) and subsequent check of pressure in residual car indicated a reading between 58-59 p.s.i. Car was susequently re-located to old rip track area in the south end of the yard to minimize any impact to the public and/or employees.    Hazmat contractor "Midwest Environmental" was contacted and requested to respond to scene after being advised of the defective PRD. Upon arrival of 'Midwest Environmental" who also confirmed leak we again attempted to align the O-Ring and O-Ring retainer with negative reults.    Supplier "Transammonia" was contacted and advised of the leak in the PRD. Supplier indicated that they could not supply for any transfer.    Do the the railcar's location in a densely populated area (Chicago Metro) and car pressure of 58-59 p.s.i. We made the following determination to degas the car based on the risk of prevailing winds in the area. While waiting for tranfer pump and deionized waster tanker to transfer vapors and any remaining product, personnel attended the car until arrival of equipment.    At 2000, CDT, 11-12-1010, degassing of car was completed and Aqueous Ammonia that was produced as a result of the transfer was taken to a nearby ammonia plant for handling. New 'Midland' O-rings and O-rings retainer were installed on PRD. Estimated volume of ammonia transferred equated to Aqua Ammonia trailer filled to 55% (7000 gallons max)with deionized water. Float rose 2% after gas went into water = 140 gallons at 5.2 lbs. per gallon (52 degrees F) equating to approximately 728 lbs of ammonia.    On 11-12-2010, Federal Railroad Administration (FRA) Inspectors A. Monroe and E. Monroe arrived on scene and were supplied requested information in regards to this Non-Accidental Release (NAR) involving this car.    Car is currently isolated in yard awaiting FRA movement approval from supplier. Protective Housing Cover was sealed with #IHBPD 000759
column169: Suggested analysis, of the "O-Ring and O-Ring" retainer from PRD for compatibility and/or defects.

column168: Univar driver picked up 1 cubic yard box of waste material from shipper.  Container was inspected before transport, and no signs of leakage were found.  Material was returned to Univar facility for cross docking to TSD site.  Upon subsequent inspection in Univar facility, box had developed a small leak on one corner of the box.  Leakage was cleaned using floor dry material, and box was overpackaged into a supersack, which also leaked material.  The container was moved to a containment pallet, pending arrival of emergency response contractor.  An emergency response company was contracted to re-package the material (including original packaging, and clean up materials) into drums.  The drums were then sent for disposal.    The cause of the failure was the presence of a small amount of free liquids within the packaged material.  The original container was not damamged; however, the liquids were released through the fiberboard box.
column169: Univar drivers will continue to inspect waste containers before pickup from custoemr and transported.  Univar has also worked with the shipper regarding the prevention of free liquids in cubic yard boxes, and shipper has committed to implementing controls to prevent reoccurrance.

column168: On Monday, November 22nd 2010 driver was taking a load of fuel to Ekalaka, MT. He was traveling in the east bound lane that was intermittent snow cover and pavement. The west bound lane had snow on it and was less traveled. The driver met a vehicle coming towards him in the west bound lane, the west bound vehicle kicked up snow causing the driver to loose sight of the road and caused him to drift to the right. The driver was to far to the right edge he tried to correct, but the trailer was sliding and pulled the truck sideways. The trailer caught in the dirt of the side of the road pulling loose from the truck and rolling also causing the truck to roll.   The truck rolled and ended up on the driver side in the road. The rollover caused the bulkhead to fail. When the truck was uprighted fuel leaked out of the double bulkhead vent until it was plugged.  Upon impact the pup trailer landed on its right side and a one foot long by four inch gash occured. This resulted in a diesel fuel release. In addition one dome cover opened. This resulted in another diesel fuel release.  A sand and gravel company was called to bring a truckload of sand to dam up the area and contain it as much as possible.
column169: There were no citations issued but, the driver was instructed to be much more cautious in adverse weather conditions.

column168: On 11/19/2010 at 15:05 hrs., personnel at the CSXT Radnor yard in Nashville, TN, discovered UTLX 210248, a residue tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., leaking from the bottom outlet of the rail car. The car was isolated away from CSXT employees and the shipper was notified thru CHEMTREC 2010-11-19-00123. A CSXT Sentinel Plus was dispatched to the scene and found that the bottom outlet handle was not in the locked and pinned position. The Sentinel placed the handle into the closed position and secured the pin into the locking slot stopping the leak.The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Artie Sturtewagen with Patriot Renewable Fuels 309-714-0329, and the car was released for transportation. This incident did require a special switching move. A QA 7.1 Non conformance report will not be required. Cause code: 148 NARRI: 5 (1+3+0) x (2+0) = 40

column168: On 11/22/2010 at approximately 17:34 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Walbridge yard in Walbridge, OH, discovered GATX 15258, a residue tank car of Ammonia Solutions, leaking from the bottom outlet valve. The car was isolated and the consignee - Terra Nitrogen Corp., the local fire department, the state DEP, the NRC and CHEMTREC, report 2010-11-22-00135, were contacted. Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet valve was open and the plug was loose. The local fire department closed the valve to stop the leak, Eagle/SWS drained the valve and replaced the bottom outlet plug tool tight. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.    Note- A CSXT employee, R.M. Shinaver, Conductor, ID# 730546, was taken to the local hospital and released after complaining of headache and eye irritation .    This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 551  NARRI: 5 (4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: AROUND 9 A.M. ON NOVEMBER 4TH 2010.  OUR DISTRICT MANAGER SCOTT OSBORNE RECEIVED A CALL FROM MARK YORK, ONE OF OUR BULK TRUCK DRIVERS.  MARK STATED TO SCOTT THAT HE WAS DELIVERING GAS TO A CUSTOMER AND SAW GAS COMING OUT OF THE BOTTOM OF HIS TRUCK.  MARK HIT HIS REMOTE EMERGENCY STOP, BUT THE GAS STILL COMING OUT FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TRUCK PIPING.  MARK WAS DELIVERING GAS TO A COMPANY THAT DOES WELDING, SO MARK REELED HIS HOSE IN AND MOVED THE CTMV A BLCOK AWAY TO A SAFER LOCATION.  MARK AGAIN HIT HIS REMOTE EMERGENCY STOP AND THE GAS WAS STILL COMING OUT.  MARK CALLED OUR OFFICE AND OUR SERVICE MANAGER, SQUIRE MUNCY AND ANOTHER DRIVER WENT TO THE SCENE.  SCOTT CALLED STEVE KRUTSINGER OF KURTSINDER SERVICE INC., A TAMPA BASED BUSINESS THAT BUILDS BULK TRUCKS.  STEVE HAD BUILT THIS TRUCK FOR OUR COMPANY IN 2002.  SCOTT EXPLAINED TO STEVE THE SITUATION THAT WE HAD A TRUCK THAT WAS LEAKING PROPANE.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE THE POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD SECURED A ONE BLOCK AREA IN EVERY DIRECTION.  BY THIS TIME THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD TWO LARGE HOSES SPRAYING WATER ON THE BULK  TRUCK IN A FOG TYPE PATTERN.  SCOTT ASKED THE FIRE DEPT. IF HE COULD APPROACH THE TRUCK TO BETTER EVALUATE THE SITUATION, AND THEY STATED NO, NOT AT THIS TIME.  SCOTT DISCUSSED HOW TO REMEDY THE SITUATION AND STOP THE LEAK.  STEVE SAID THE PIPING AND THE DELIVERY HOSE NEEDED TO BE DRAINED IN ORDER FOR THE LEAK TO COMPLETELY STOP.  SCOTT INSTRUCTED A FIREMAN ON HOW TO OPEN THE VALVE ON THE DELIVERY HOSE AND DRAIN THE GAS OUT OF THE HOSE AND TRUCK PIPING.  STEVE WENT TO HIS TRUCK AND GOT A GLOBE VALVE TO ATTACH TO THE END OF OUR NOZZLE ON THE DELIVERY HOSE.  THIS ALLOWS A CONTROLLED RELEASE OF PROPANE.  THE FIREMAN TOOK THE DELIVERY HOSE BACK INTO THE WATER FOG, SO WHEN HE RELEASED IT, IT WOULD DISSIPATE.  THE FIREMAN OPENED THE GLOBE VALVE ALLOWING THE GAS TO GO FROM LIQUID TO VAPOR.  ONCE THAT HAPPENDED, THEY TURNED OFF THE WATER HOSES THAT HAD BEEN FOGGING THE TRUCK, AND THE LEAK HAD STOPPED.  THE TRUCK WAS THEN TAKEN OVER TO KRUTSINGER SERVICES FOR REPAIRS.

column169: Securing cargo has been re-evaluated. Additional load lock bars and ratchet securing straps have been supplied to all vehicles. Door security has been enhanced on all vehicles by placing pad locks on the tops and bottoms of cargo doors that are considered critical points for secuting cargo area. This enhances cargo security as a double means in case of unforeseen breach securing the cargo. All drivers have been instructed of these procedures for transport of all cargos. Training on the securing cargo and inspecting the security of cargo doors for transporting hazardous materials was held on November 17, 2010.

column168: Driver was using air pressure to transfer product from the cargo tank to the customer storage tank inside the building.    The storage tank didn’t have a sight glass or monitor to measure how full it was.  Plant operator uses a ladder to look inside the dome of the tank.  The dome is also used to vent the tank.  The driver had understood that the plant operator would be monitoring the level.  Driver said he closed valves and went inside to see how full it was.  He said the product had splashed/bubbled out of dome as tank was being filled.  About 1 gallon on the floor.   Operator told driver he was using too much air pressure.  Driver went back to continue the unload by just cracking the valve on the trailer a little bit.  While the rest of the unload took place, 2 plant operators were cleaning up the one gallon spill.  When the line went empty, a mist was forced out the dome into the area by the plant operators.  One immediately went outside to vomit.  The other went to close a door so it wouldn’t get into the plant.  Both men went to the hospital to be checked out.  The one that vomited was released.  The other one was kept overnight as a precaution and to do some breathing tests. He was released the next morning and we have no further details.
column169: The driver did partially close his valve to prevent splattering out of the storage tank but he should also have reduced the air pressure.  The set-up of the storage tank could also have been designed better to allow the dome to be closed and a separate vent and sight glass installed.

column168: AROUND 21:10 CALLED FOR A RESPONDER BECAUSE SHE HAD A LEAKING PACKAGE ON THE PD3 BELT.  THE RESPONDER DONNED PPE, WENT TO PD3, CLEANED THE SPILL AREA AND BROUGHT THE PACKAGE BACK TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA.  WHEN HE OPENED IT HE NOTICED THAT THREE OF THE SOILED BOTTLES IN THE BOX HAD D.O.T. CLASS 8 SYMBOLS ON THE PRODUCT LABEL.  THE LABEL ALSO SAID POISION AND WARNING CORROSIVE.  THREE OTHER BOTTLES THAT WERE DIFFERENT PRODUCTS BY THE SAME MANUFACTURER HAD THE "PHRASE HAZARDOUS INGREDIENTS" AS WELL AS THE INGREDIENTS MARKED OUT IN BLACK PEN.  THE RESPONDER WAS ABLE TO SEE WHAT WAS MARKED OUT WHEN THE INK WAS REMOVED BY THE SPILL RESIDUE.  THE HAZMAT SUPPORT CENTER SAID TO LOCATE THE MSDS SO THE RESPONDER PUT IN A REQUEST WITH THE MANUFACTURER ONLINE.
column169: THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS THAT NO INTERNAL PACKAGING WAS USED AND THE FRAGILE PRODUCTS WERE AGAINST THE CARTON WALL.  RECOMMEND THAT ALL LIQUIDS BE PACKED UPRIGHT AND THAT AT LEAST 2 INCHES OF PACKAGING BE USED TO PROTECT ALL SIDES OF THE CONTENTS FROM THE WALL OF THE BOX.  FURTHER RECOMMEND THAT THE BOX BE NEW AND AT LEAST BURST 200 ECT 32 AND APPROPRIATE FOR THE HAZMATS BEING SHIPPED AND THAT ALL HAZARDOUS PAPERWORK AND MARKINGS BE ACCURATE AND PRESENT ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX.

A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shipper’s location and arrived at the drum transfer facility in South Portland ME. During transfer of the drum in question the driver identified the non bulk package leaking from lid/gasket at the top of the container. Approximately half a cup of waste paint leaked from the drum and contacted the transfer facility's dock. The driver immediately contained the release using appropriate personal protective equipment, wiped up the paint with a rag and placed the rag into the drum; applied a new lid and gasket to the drum and applied the proper closure procedures. This operation was completed and once the container was re-secured, the drum continued on to its intended destination.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a  thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to  either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated.

column168: (A) Residue chlorine tank car OLNX 114053 was involved in a multi-car train derailment that resulted in a small crack above the center line in the side of the car.  The crack allowed approximately 313 pounds of residue material to escape in vapor form.  A patch was applied to the crack to stop the release and capture the remaining material.  All remaining material was contained and properly disposed of and the car was cleaned and purged. The damaged car was loaded on a flatcar and moved to Augusta, GA, where it is awaiting further disposition. (B)SCMX 4309 was involved in a multi-car derailment that resulted in a puncture of the B-end tank head allowing the entire contents of the car to escape.  The car was cleaned and purged of all liquid and vapors.  The car was loaded on a flatcar and is in Augusta, GA, awaiting final disposition. Environmental clean up and restoration efforts continue.  All recovered material was properly disposed of.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On November 23rd 2010 at approximately 1100 hours an IMTT operator completed the loading of a Volume Transport tanker truck when he noticed product (n-propanol) dripping from an internal valve.  The IMTT operator immediately placed a 5-gallon pail under the tanker compartment to collect the dripping product.  The IMTT operator then called his supervisor who dispacthed EQ Terminal Services who is IMTT's emergency response contractor.  EQ dispatched a clean tanker trailer to remove the product from the leaking trailer and off load it to the original above ground storage tank from which the product was being stored.  The driver of the Volume Transport truck informed IMTT that he would return the next day with a new trailer.
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product to inform them of the incident. The customer subsequently contacted the transportation company and will address any mechanical or structural issues with the truck or related components.

The original loader conducted a turnover to another loader for a break and walked thru the rack at 1445. Covering loader walked the rack and gauged each tank car level and continued to load the railcars.While loading CBO, on car GATX 24665 the loading arm extension sleeve that directs the flow into the top of the railcar came unhooked and dropped down about 7 inches. This caused a gap between the loading arm and the extension. The cause of the sleeve becoming unhooked from the loading arm was due to extreme high winds and vibration. The gap between the loading arm and the extension coupled with the extreme high winds caused the CBO to blow outside of the extension onto the top and along the sides of the railcar. Loader noticed the CBO flowing from the top of the extension and immediately blocked the product valve to loading spot. Loader then immediatley notified his supervisor, lead loader, and original loader about the incident.
column169: Come up with a system that will be safer in all weather conditions.

column168: Please note, Schenker, Inc. shall be named as reporting party only.According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While loading a trailer at the Schenker, Inc. facility, three (3) 55-gallon drums fell from the pallet. Two (2) drums released their contents, while the third was damaged,yet in tact. The free product released to the trailer floor, warehouse dock, and asphalt. Schenker, Inc. employees performed the cleanup utilizing absorbent pads and pillows on the free liquid. The spent material was containerized into four (4) 55-gallon drums. Eagle/SWS was contacted to assess the site. Upon arrival on site, all free product had been recovered. However, the cleanup had utilized a wash hose to wash down the affected area, and product was detected within the storm drain, upon inspection. Eagle/SWS proceeded to utilize their pressure washer and vac truck to flush the sewer system, broke down the contaminated pallet, and overpacked the three (3) damaged drums into salvage drums, pending disposal. Eagle/SWS returned to the site, during daylight hours, to perform additional cleanup, following site inspection from Miami-Dade County representative. Disposal will be coordinated in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. Per discussion with Luis Estrada of Miami-Dade County Environmental, site has been cleared, and no further cleanup action remains.
column169: Schenker, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Our driver took his eye off the road and veared toward the ditch.  The tires went off the edge of the road and the driver over corrected when trying to bring the truck back on the road and the truck and tanker overturned and rolled.  We had another driver in the area that came upon the accident and he checked on the driver then called 911 and the local fire department and ambulance where the first on scene.  Once the driver called 911 he then called the office to notify us of the accident.  The office notified the appropriate authorities.  The second driver and the local fire department determined that there was a samll crack that was leaking near the front of the trailer and they plugged it to stop as much as possible and also contained the product that had spilled.  They then pumped out the compartment to stop the leak completely. Once the tank was empty the wrecker uprighted the truck and pulled out the tanker.  Our Emergency Response Spill team arrived on scene and accesed the contamination.  Eventually there was 50 yards of dirt excavated, hauled away and replaced with 50 yards of clean dirt and seeded.  The supplamental reports will include the release from the South Dakota Department of Natural Resources and WCEC our Hazmat Emergency Response company along with a written company accident report.
column169: In this accident it was an error in judgement by the driver.  We continue to do driver training on a regular basis along with training with our insurance company for drivers and other company personnel.  We try to provide pictures of incidents like this and pictures from accidents from other companies to continue to bring more awareness to drivers of how fast something can happen when mistakes are made along with how quickly it can affect their employment.

column168: DURING A SCHEDULED POLE-MOUNTED TRANSFORMER REPLACEMENT, THE (2) TRANSFORMERS WHICH WERE BRACKETED TOGETHER WERE LOWERED DOWN TO THE VEHICLE FLAT BED.  THE TRANSFORMERS WERE RELEASED FROM THE HOIST CABLE ONTO THE FLAT BED WHEN THEY TIPPED OVER.  2 BUSHINGS ON THE TRANSFORMERS WERE BROKEN WHEN THEY TIPPED OVER, CAUSING A COMBINED RELEASE OF 10 GALLONS OF MINERAL OIL TO THE SURFACE OF THE FLAT BED AND THEN TO THE SOIL BELOW.  A SAN DIEGO GAS AND ELECTRIC HAZMAT CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO INITIATE THE CLEANUP.  THE TRANSFORMERS WERE UNMARKED FOR PCB CONTENT.  THE SPILL WAS TREATED AS PCB CONTAINING MINERAL OIL AND THE OIL WAS ANALYZED BY SAN DIEGO GAS AND ELCTRIC LABORATORY.  THE ANALYTICAL RESULTS SHOWED THE MINERAL OIL CONTAINED 510 PPM OF PCB IN THE 10 GALLON CAPACITY TRANSFORMER AND 2.4 PPM PCM IN  THE 5 GALLON CAPACITY TRANSFORMER.  THE SPILL CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED PER MEGA RULE 761.  ALL IMPACTED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND SOIL ANALYSIS WAS COMPLETED.  BACKFILL WAS COMPLETED USING CLEAN SOIL.  NO WATERWAYS WERE AFFECTED.  THE VEHICLE WAS NOT IN TRASPORT DURING THIS INCIDENT AND NO PUBLIC ROADS WERE AFFECTED.
column169: REFRESHER TRAINING WAS PROVIDED TO EMPLOYEES ON THE PROPER HANDLING OF OIL FIELD EQUIPMENT DURING THE LOADING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES.  PROCEDURES FOR CLUSTER-MOUNTED (BRACKETED) TRANSFORMERS HAVE BEEN REVISED.  CLUSTER-MOUNTED TRANSFORMERS WILL BE REMOVED ONE AT A TIME RATHER THAN AS A SET OR COMBINED UNIT.

column168: Intermodal container HDMU 470299 was reported at the BNSF intermodal facility leaking an unknown substance.  HDMU 470299 was taken to the containment area within this intermodal facility.  HDMU 470299 was an import shipment from South Korea (Republic of Korea) that arrived earlier on a BNSF train.  Response contractor inspected HDMU 470299 finding one, 55-gallon steel drum (UN Spec 1A1/X1.5/300/10/ROK/KR 10-102) towards the rear doorway with a small puncture hole at this drum's bottom head next to the bottom rim.  This puncture appeared to be caused by impaction from a nail or other sharp object.  The compromised drum was placed into an overpack drum, properly labeled and set aside in a safe location for consignee representatives to pick-up at a later date.  The small amount of spillage within HDMU 470299 was cleaned after an absorbent applied.  Also, a small amount of spillage atop an asphalted area was cleaned.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE, BUT UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE WHICH CONTAINED GERMANIUM-68 SOLID POLYMER, THEY NOTICED ONE OF THE INNER PACKAGES CONTAINING 253 MBq Ge-68 WAS MISSING.  I WAS CONTACTED AT 13:10 ON TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 23, 2010 BY SIEMENS EMPLOYEE CHRISTI ELAM TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  I IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED OUR FEDEX RADIATION CONSULTANT, DR ROY PARKER.  I SPENT A SIGNIFICANT AMOUNT OF TIME CONTACTING ALL OF THE LOCATIONS THIS PACKAGE HAD TRAVELED, INCLUDING FARGO, ND, GRAND FORKS, ND, MEMPHIS, TN, & KNOXVILLE, TN.  IT HAD BEEN SNOWING IN FARGO, RAINING IN GRAND FORKS, MEMPHIS & KNOXVILLE WHICH MAY HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THE BOX BEING SLIGHTLY COMPROMISED.  AN ALL-POINTS ALERT WAS ISSUED AND FEDEX EMPLOYEES WERE CHECKING FOR THIS MISSING INNER PACKAGE. FINALLY ON FRIDAY, NOVEMEBER 26, AROUND 1300, THE MISSING SHIPMENT WAS FOUND AT THE FEDEX STATION THAT HAD DELIVERED THE PACKAGE ON TUESDAY.  THE BOX HAD COME OUT AND HAD BEEN MISTAKENLY SET ASIDE UNTIL FEDEX SECURITY FOUND THE PACKAGE. THE CONSIGNEE WAS CONTACTED AND FEDEX QUICKLY PREPARED THE SHIPMENT IN CORRECT PACKAGING, WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF OUR FEDEX RADIATION CONSULTANT.  THE CONSIGNEE PICKED UP THE PACKAGE AND THE SEARCH ENDED.

column169: PLACE DUNNAGE UNDER DRUMS, BAGS, PAILS AND TOTES TO PREVENT SHARP OR POINTED OBJECTS FROM PUNCTURING THE BOTTOM. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON BOTTOM; LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: This release occurred during the loading of roll-off boxes onto a straight truck. There were two (2) roll-off boxes containing the same material that were being loaded at different times at the Heritage Transport, LLC 10-Day facility.  The first box was being loaded onto the truck and the driver observed material was spilling from the tailgate of the roll-off box.  He retuned the roll-off box to the ground, contacted a supervisor to look at the box and assisted with the loading of the box onto the truck.  During the loading process the box released some material.  Once the box was on the truck the material ceased leaking from the box and the box was transported to Heritage-WTI, Inc. for treatment.  At that time spill pads and vermiculite were placed on the affected area.  The second box was visually inspected for free liquids and it was determined by supervisory staff that there were none, and the roll-off box could be loaded onto the truck. When the second box was loaded onto the trailer, material began to leak from the tailgate in a manner similar to the initial roll-off box.  The roll-off box was loaded onto the truck and the material once again ceased to leak and the box was transported to Heritage-WTI, Inc.  Spill pads and vermiculite were placed on the affected area.  A total of approximately 10 gallons of material was released from the two (2) roll-off boxes.  The material in both boxes was: UN3077, WASTE ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES, SOLID, N.O.S., 9, PO III, (F037, F038).  Emergency response and clean-up was handled by the Field Services group from Heritage-WTI, Inc.  Response efforts included vacuuming accumulated stormwater and spilled liquids and excavating gravel in the affected areas.  All materials were properly disposed of at Heritage-WTI, Inc. column168: At 1930 hours, the propane truck had off-loaded its contents and was preparing to enter the Osterman facility. An estimated 100 gallons of liquid propane remained in truck. The driver backed-up Blanchard Street, and accidentally backed-over a telephone pole in front of the Osterman facility. The pole broke, and electrical wires dropped and started a fire in the cab. The Fire Department was called. They decided to let the fire burn, and evacuated a 0.75 mile radius. The propane tank and diesel tanks remained intact. The incident ended at approximately midnight, when the FD declared the scene under control.
column169: All truck drivers have been advised to be cautious when turning around or backing-up from Blanchard Road, especially with regards to telephone poles.

column168: EMPLOYEE WAS MAKING A DELIVERY TO A COMMERCIAL CUSTOMER IN THE DARK USING A FLASH LIGHT.  UPON LOOKING ATHTE REAR OF THE BOBTAIL HE NOTICED WORK LIGHTS THAT WOULD ASSIST IN LIGHTING UP THE WORK AREA.  THE EMPLOYEE STOPPED THE TRANSFER OF PROPANE AND WLKED TO THE BOBTAIL TO TURN ON THE SWITCH.  WHEN THE EMPLOYEE FLIPPED THE LIGHT SWITCH A SHORT IN THE WIRING CAUSED THE TRUCK TO STALL.  THE EMPLOYEE MADE MULTIPLE ATTEMPTS TO RESTART THE TRUCK AND COULD NOT GET IT TO TURN OVER.  AFTER ABOUT 20 MINUTES THE EMPLOYEE TURNED THE LIGHT SWITCH OFF AND THE TRUCK RESTARTED IMMEDIATELY.  THE EMPLOYEE DECIDED TO GET THE TRUCK BACK TO THE YARD BEFORE ANY OTHER ISSUES OCCURED AND DROVE AWAY FROM THE CUSTOMER LOCATION.  THE EMPLOYEE NEVER DISCONNECTED THE HOSE FROM THE CUSTOMERS TANK, OR PICKED UP HIS EQUIPMENT AT THE TANK.  THE HOSE REEL (APPROXIMATELY 150') UNREELED TEH REMAINDER OF THE WAY AND SHEARED AT THE CONNECTION POINT ON THE TRUCK.  ONCE THE DRIVER ARRIVED BACK AT THE YARD A POLICE OFFICER WAS WAITING FOR HIM TO ENSURE THAT HE HAD NOT BEEN KIDNAPPED, BASED ON THE FINDINGS AT THE CUSTOMERR LOCATION.  ALL RELEASED LIQUID DISCIPATED IMMEDIATELY AND NO EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS NECESSARY.  THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS LESS THAN 1 MINUTE.
column169: A REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT PARTICULARS AND NEED TO PAY ATTENTION TO THE TASK AT HAND WAS CONDUCTED WITH ALL EMPLOYEES FOLLOWING THE EVENT.  THE EMPLOYEE IN QUESTION WAS TERMINATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE AMERIGAS PULL-AWAY POLICY.  ALL NEW TRUCKS ARE EQUIPPED WITH BRAKE INTERLOCK SWITCHES THAT PREVENT THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT IF THE HOSE NOZZLE IS NOT IN THE CRADDLE.  THIS PARTICULAR VEHICLE WAS AN OLDER MODEL THAT HAD NOT YET BEEN RETROFITTED

column168: I would like to assure you this spill was not a discharge to the waters of the United States. This discharge was caused by a motor vehicle accident which caused our tanker to be overturned and a spill to accumulate in a roadside field which was dry prior the accident. The spill was contained via berms and dikes until it could be removed and properly disposed of the same day.  This product PG76-22 (Petroleum Asphalt Liquid), is used as a binding agent in the manufacturing of commonly used hot mix asphalt. This hot mix asphalt is prominent in most highways, roadways and parking lots in the United States. The product is only considered as a hazardous material because of its elevated temperature of 380 degrees Fahrenheit during its transit. Therefore, it must be placarded as “3257 HOT” (Elevated temperature liquid, n.o.s., at or above 100 C and below its flash point (including molten metals, molten salts, etc.).  The discharge occurred because of a motor vehicle accident. On November 11th 2010 at approximately 7:05 am, our tanker truck was Northbound on Hwy 11 in Etowah County, when a work van pulled out onto the roadway and hit the left front of the truck causing damage to the steering which would not allow our driver (Michael Page) to correct the roll effect of the accident, thus caused the tanker truck to overturn. Our driver was able to remove himself from the overturned vehicle within the next couple of minutes after the accident. Upon inspection, Mr. Page noticed the tanker leaking product from the fill lid and reported this to our Transportation Supervisor, Phillip Ray. The discharge occurred in the vicinity of 34-09.225N & 85-57.236W. The damage to the tanker allowed the fill port to become unsealed and the PG76-22 product to escape through the opening.  At approximately 7:15 am, I directed Michael Knight to dike the area with a virgin Limestone aggregate to eliminate the spread of the product in the affected area. This eliminated the spread of the hot liquid. The spilled PG76-22 product was allowed to cool for proper handling, where by, heavy equipment was brought in to accommodate the removal of the spilled product. Large amounts of virgin Limestone aggregate (8910), was brought onsite to incorporate with the product for better handling. It was then removed from the site and taken to our plant location and stored for future use in the production of hot mix asphalt.The removal was completed at approximately 1500 hrs for a duration of approximately 8 hours.
column169: This was a motor vehicle accident which was caused by a third party outside of the control of Good Hope Contracting Co., Inc. and is considered to be a non-preventable accident from our Company’s standpoint. However, the environmental impact was mitigated to a minor event, with no lasting impact on the environment.    I have cautioned the drivers of our tankers to be careful with people which are waiting to pull onto the roadway from an adjacent driveway.

column168: A River Valley Cooperative employee was pulling a 1,000 gallon nurse tank containing anhydrous ammonia to a farm field located near 155th Avenue in rural Burlington, Iowa.  At the intersection of 155th Avenue and 55th Street in Des Moines County, Iowa, the employee turned too severly and the nurse tank rolled into the road ditch.  The nurse tank valve was turned into the "on" or "open" position due to the roll.  This caused the anhydrous ammonia to be released into the atmosphere.  The driver removed himself from the hazardous situation and contacted local law enforcement and local fire department for assistance.  No additional mitigation efforts were made as the entire product was released before an apporpriate HAZMAT could arrive.  The driver conducted himself appropriately to remove himself from the immediate hazard and contact authorities.  The duration of the release was approximately 1 hour.
column169: Incident has been used by River Valley Cooperative to illustrate the need for use of safe driving techniques when transporting hazardous materials.  In addition, the company will use the incident to confirm the driver's safe and appropriate actions when dealing with an anhydrous ammonia release.  He did exactly what he should have done, remove himself from the situation and contact law enforcement and fire department to assist in the stopping of the release.  The driver made an appropriate decision to remove himself from a potentially life threatening situation by exposure to an anhydrous cloud.

column168: A SEMI TRACTOR/TRAILER WAS HAULING DRUMS OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID IN A 53' VAN TRAILER.  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE PULLED OVER AT A TRUCK STOP AND NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING NEAR THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  AT THIS POINT ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT WAS CONTACTED AND A LOCAL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO THE TRUCK STOP TO MITIGATE THE RELEASE.  UPON ARRIVING ON SITE, THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CREW NOTICED APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD IMPACTED THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA.  THE REAR DOORS OF THE TRAILER WERE OPENED AND THE DRUMS WERE SLOWLY OFF LOADED WITH A FORKLIFT UNTIL THE LEAKING DRUM WAS LOCATED NEAR THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM A VERY SMALL HOLE NEAR THE BOTTOM OF A 55 GALLON POLY DRUM.  A DEFINITE CAUSE OF THE LEAK COULD NOT BE DETERMINED, HOWEVER THE CREW ON SITE NOTICED THAT THE LOAD WAS NOT SECURED PROPERLY AS IT WAS SECURED ONLY BY A SINGLE RATCHET STRAP ACROSS THE BACK OF THE DRUMS AND IT HAD COME LOOSE AND WAS LAYING ON THE FLOOR WHEN THE TRAILER WAS OPENED.  THE DRUM COULD HAVE POTENTIALLY BEEN DAMAGED AS A RESULT OF THE LOAD SHIFTING ALONG THE UNEVEN TRAILER FLOOR.  THE MATERIAL THAT HAD LEAKED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WAS ABSORBED USING GRANULE ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE MATERIAL ON THE ASPHALT WAS ALSO ABSORBED USING GRANULE ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  ALL CONTAMINATED ABSORBENTS WERE DRUMMED AND TRANSPORTED OFF SITE FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: Anyone providing a material for transport should be trained on proper loading and blocking and bracing procedures in order to prevent a load from shifting during transport.
